        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>765</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">FA-000G</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>FA-000G.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Metric Space">Metric Space</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors />
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>A metric space is a set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M]]></fr:tex> together with a <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0009.xml" addr="FA-0009" title="Distance Measure">distance measure</fr:link> (or metric) <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[d]]></fr:tex> that defines a concept of distance between any two members of the set.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>The metric satisfies the following properties:</fr:p>
            <fr:ul><fr:li>Non-negativity: <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[d(x,y) \geq  0]]></fr:tex></fr:li>
<fr:li>Identity of indiscernibles: <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[d(x,y) = 0]]></fr:tex> if and only if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x = y]]></fr:tex></fr:li>
<fr:li>Symmetry: <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[d(x,y) = d(y,x)]]></fr:tex></fr:li>
<fr:li>Triangle inequality: <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[d(x,z) \leq  d(x,y) + d(y,z)]]></fr:tex></fr:li></fr:ul>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>766</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">FA-000E</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>FA-000E.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Sup norm">Sup norm</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors />
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>The sup norm (or supremum norm, or uniform norm, or <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L^\infty ]]></fr:tex> norm) of a bounded function <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f: X \rightarrow  \mathbb {R}]]></fr:tex> (or <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex>) is defined as:</fr:p>
            <fr:p>
              <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[||f||_\infty  = \sup _{x \in  X} |f(x)|]]></fr:tex>
            </fr:p>
            <fr:p>where <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\sup ]]></fr:tex> denotes the supremum, or least upper bound, of the set of values.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>For the space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[C(X)]]></fr:tex> of continuous functions on a compact set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex>, the sup norm makes <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[C(X)]]></fr:tex> into a <fr:link type="local" href="FA-000F.xml" addr="FA-000F" title="Banach Space">Banach space</fr:link>.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>The sup norm measures the maximum absolute value that a function attains on its domain.</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
      </fr:mainmatter>
      <fr:backmatter />
    </fr:tree>
  </fr:backmatter>
